Senior staff members of the Nigeria Postal Service (NIPOST) under the aegis of the Senior Staff of Statutory Corporations and Government Owned Companies (SSASCGOC), have disclosed that about 15,000 jobs are at risk due to the current impasse on stamp duty. The NIPOST union has also given the Federal Government a 21-day ultimatum to resolve the impasse on stamp duty between NIPOST and the Federal Inland Revenue Service (FIRS). Addressing journalists in Abuja, SSASCGOC general secretary, Ayo Olurunfemi, said that if the federal government fails to meet their request, the union shall have no other option than to direct that all its members in NIPOST should withdraw their services. He explained that the union recognises the power conferred on FIRS to collect stamp duties just as that of the NIPOST power to produce and issue stamps. He said, “these must be acknowledged and recognised in implementing the Finance Act. Therefore, FIRS’ production of stamps to denote duties, is illegal. It should be procured from NIPOST. The fact remains that stamp is a product of NIPOST as given to it by law. “The Finance Act did not give any power to FIRS to produce stamp. In other words, to utilise stamp for duties, FIRS must get it from NIPOST. The FIRS, on 30th June 2020, against any known law,  produced and launched its owned brand of adhesive stamp, thereby hijacking and taking over the function of NIPOST. “As we speak, many Nigerians have stopped purchasing adhesive stamps from NIPOST. This, if not challenged and nip in the bud, will ultimately lead to the collapse of NIPOST, and the staff will have to lose their jobs. We will not allow this to happen,” Olorunfemi added. 